			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2011</a> keynote:</span><br><i>Towards a One-Stop-Shop for Analysis, Transformation and Visualization of Software</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/PaulKlint.html">Paul Klint</a>, <a href="../profile/BertLisser.html">Bert Lisser</a>, <a href="../profile/AtzevanderPloeg.html">Atze van der Ploeg</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_1">10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_1</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It extends Rascal/IMP into a more complete workbench for analysis, transformation, and visualization.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Rascal is presented as the underlying meta-programming language used to implement these capabilities.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s central contribution is an integrated software visualization framework layered over Rascal.
</li></ul></li></ul>
